A Bib too far

Author

Lucas McGill

Published

October 6, 2025

Intro

This documents my turbulent attempts to generate a BibTeX bibliography on PDF remediation using an LLM. Through a series of prompts I will demonstrate the difficulties LLMs have generating accurate bibliographies. My experience with this experiment leads me to believe that some things are still best done the old-fashioned way.

First attempt

Initial prompt

generate a BibTeX .bib file for these three sources from acm digital library:

https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/3507661 https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/3582298.3582299 https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/3706598.3713084

Initial result

My first attempt was in ChatGPT. I wanted to start pretty basic because I remember when LLMs exploded on the scene a major criticism was that students were using them to write research papers and the LLMs were fabricating facts and citations. I began with asking to generate just three BibTeX entries from acm.org URLs. It was able to get the first one mostly correct, but the second pointed to another article, while the third generated an output full of â???.â This is actually surprising behavior for an LLM because I am used to it being confidently wrong. In this case, It at least gave me the grace to easily see that it couldnât generate the BibTeX entry from that URL. This first output indicated that I was about to be in for a frustrating experience.

Second attempt

Prompt

I think we are missing the full citations. ACM digital libraries has an export button on the article page that allows the user to export the BibTeX citation. Can we use that?

Result

Within the same chat as the first prompt, I wanted to see if I could point the LLM to the location of the BibTeX entry on the ACM page. If I revealed where the information was located, would it be able to perform a bit of web scraping to collect the information. I think it was funny that it suggested I grab the BibTeX from ACM and paste them into the prompt input. If I can copy and paste these entries? Why would I use a middleman?

Disclaimer

Before we continue, I want to address that the output of the last seven attempts did not give me confidence that I could brute force an accurate .bib file from ChatGPT by just going off vibes. I began doing research on what BibTeX is, how an LLM might generate an accurate .bib, and how I was going to validate the .bib once it was generated. My research was conducted through Google and DuckDuckGo searches, as well as with Gemini, ChatGPT, and Claude. I actually donât mind using an LLM as a search engine to conduct research as long as it gives me the sources so that I can verify the information. Iâm not going to post the prompts I used for that research here, because it was just research and not attempts. After conducting some research that didnât provide me with any surefire methods. I decided that maybe I needed a more specific tool rather than the default ChatGPT. I thought I would ask Gemini about training my own bot on BibTeX to see how difficult that might be. The next few prompts are my exchange with Gemini, including output from Gemini for a highly specific prompt to generate a .bib that I ultimately edited and used for this assignment.

Eigth attempt

Prompt

can i create a chatbot that is trained on bibtex format to generate a .bib file from a list of dois?

Result

Gemini gave me a rather long output, but I will post the first few sentences that indicated to me that my approach was unnecessary.

Output:

Yes, you absolutely can create a tool that generates a .bib file from a list of DOIs, 
and a chatbot can be a great user interface for it.

However, you don't need to "train" a model on the BibTeX format from scratch. BibTeX has 
a well-defined, rule-based structure. The task is more about data retrieval and 
formatting rather than complex language understanding.

- **Final Validation:** Before presenting the output, perform a final syntax check on the entire file to ensure there are no missing commas, mismatched brackets, or other formatting errors.

abstract = {People with visual impairments use assistive technology, e.g., screen readers, to navigate and read PDFs. This is great. No need for further edits. Now can you provide the entire .bib from the correct entries in the original output to the edits in the next output and the entries in the final output?

Result

This is basically when I had decided to give up trying to get ChatGPT to output one accurate, unified .bib. ChatGPT only displayed 15 of the original 25 entries. The 15 entries did appear to be legitimate entries however. At this point I was working for the machine more than the machine was working for me. I did not know how to recover from the drift, and I was running out of time to start the process over again and complete this document.

Conclusion

I knew this assignment would be frustrating when I was first reading the instructions. One of the first major criticisms of LLMs was that they generate bogus citations. They seem to have gotten a bit better at this in a short time but have a long ways to go in my opinion. I studied writing & rhetoric in undergrad, so I donât have much trouble conducting research and finding relevant sources. This was my key frustration with this assignment. Had the assignment been to just go and find 20 sources on PDF remediation and compile them into a .bib, I could have done that in under an hour. And the folks at ACM have made this easy for us. A simple click on the export button on any article I found on ACM provides you with a perfect BibTeX entry, but this isnât BibTeX class, this is Prompt Engineering.

I think there is so much more I need to learn about interfacing with the machine to make it work effectively for me. However, with this in mind, I began to wonder about its use case. If I must spend years learning how to effectively prompt for something like a .bib, is this technology really maximizing human productivity? In my research for this assignment, I began watching YouTube videos made by so-called âPrompt Engineers.â I realized that there is no unifying opinion on how one best interfaces with the machine. And it seems like it is hard to come to some concrete conclusions because we donât know precisely how these things work.

Now donât get me wrong, I think this tool can be used effectively in specific areas such as brainstorming and certain research, but I am not convinced that this is the technology to usher in the age of WALL-E. Which if you are unfamiliar, WALL-E is a film where humans have destroyed the planet and are now living obese lives on a space station where everything is automated for them. I spent hours validating the results of my output. This was infuriating in the context of this assignment. However, if I knew I was in some way directly contributing to making LLMs more accurate, I would have found it to be more worthwhile, and maybe with this knowledge I may be able to make that kind of contribution in the future. I canât wait to find out what I was doing wrong from the other students in the class who seem more knowledgeable than me on the topic. Maybe my assertions are all wrong. Anyway, Iâm not upset about this. I joined this class because there is so much hype around this technology and I wanted to be able to talk and think critically about it. I personally am not convinced that it is a major threat, nor a panacea for all our problems. I think it is a tool, but you wouldnât use a hammer to tighten a screw. A tool has certain specific use cases, and it is important to know the limitations and the possibilities.
